# Testing

- For timely local development, prefer the `_fast` debug variant
  (e.g. `make core_debug_fast`), which builds with `-DDEBUG -g -O3`.

## Unit tests

Exactly ONE concrete System Under Test; every other dependency is mocked.
Mocks are small structs supplied as the SUT's template parameters, using gmock
`MOCK_METHOD`.

```cpp
struct MockGetGoalCandidateRuleIds {
    MOCK_METHOD(MockRuleIdSet&, get, (const goal_lineage*));
};
using test_conflict_detector_t = conflict_detector<MockGetGoalCandidateRuleIds>;
```

## Integration tests

Exercise how multiple CONCRETE systems compose together (unlike unit tests).
Some infrastructure may still be mocked, but the point is real cross-system
interplay via a manifest.

## Style

Tests favor less abstraction. Prefer straightforward, readable setup over DRY
factoring; some duplication is acceptable when it keeps a test self-contained.
